create (_2557:`Organization` {`cdcEntity`:"", `contactName`:"", `emailContact`:"", `fullName`:"National Center for Health Statistics", `fullNameDivision`:"", `id`:"O14", `informationValidated`:"No", `informationValidatedBy`:"", `informationValidatedOn`:"", `lastUpdated`:"", `lastUpdatedBy`:"", `locationCity`:"", `locationState`:"", `mission`:"As the Nation’s principal health statistics agency, the National Center for Health Statistics (NCHS) compiles statistical information to guide actions and policies to improve the health of our people. We are a unique public resource for health information –-a critical element of public health and health policy. Working with partners throughout the health community, we use a variety of approaches to efficiently obtain information from the sources most able to provide information. We collect data from birth and death records, medical records, interview surveys, and through direct physical exams and laboratory testing. NCHS is a key element of our national public health infrastructure, providing important surveillance information that helps identify and address critical health problems. Information is at the core of our mission. NCHS employs a staff of over 600 in two locations - in Hyattsville, Maryland, outside Washington, D.C., and in Research Triangle Park, North Carolina.  The Center Director is Charles Rothwell. ", `missionLastUpdatedDate`:"", `name`:"National Center for Health Statistics", `phoneContact`:"", `shortName`:"NCHS", `shortNameDivision`:""})

create (_2793:`Program` {`CR_DATE_CREATED`:1428674800793, `CR_DATE_EDITED`:"", `CR_DATE_EXECUTED`:1428687735347, `CR_NODE_TYPE`:"Program", `CR_PREVIOUS`:"{\"name\":\"BioSense Program\",\"id\":\"P3\",\"purpose\":\"The BioSense Program was created by congressional mandate as part of the Public Health Security and Bioterrorism Preparedness and Response Act of 2002, and it was launched by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) in 2003. BioSense is a near real-time surveillance system that receives and processes electronic healthcare encounter data, including, chief complaints, final diagnosis codes, procedure codes, clinical laboratory, pharmacy prescription, and patient demographic data from participating public health jurisdictions’ non-federal hospital emergency departments and inpatient facilities in addition to all United States Department of Defense (DoD) and Veterans Affairs (VA) outpatient hospitals and clinics nationwide. The BioSense Program also receives pharmacy data from a private sector health information exchange firm and laboratory data from two national level private sector clinical laboratories. The BioSense Program is in the process of transitioning from the original BioSense application to the BioSense 2.0 application that has new governance, a new organizational structure, and a new process for data submission and management. The Association of State and Territorial Health Officials (ASTHO) has been funded through a cooperative agreement with CDC’s Division of Notifiable Disease and Healthcare Information (DNDHI) within the Public Health Surveillance and Informatics Program Office (PHSIPO) of the Office of Surveillance, Epidemiology, and Laboratory Services (OSELS) to facilitate the governance of BioSense 2.0, and through a contract with a vendor, ASTHO will offer access and use of BioSense 2.0 on a voluntary basis to state, local, and territorial health jurisdictions. Unlike the BioSense 1.0 application where participating organizations’ data were processed and stored at CDC in the CDC owned and operated Information Technology Services Office’s Mid-Tier Data Center on secure servers, all data submitted by users in BioSense 2.0 will reside in a cloud-enabled, web-based platform that sits in the secure, private Government Cloud and is in compliance with the Federal Information Security Management Act. The platform will provide users with an exclusive secure space as well as tools for posting, receiving, controlling, analyzing, and sharing their public health surveillance information with other public health jurisdictions, CDC, or other public health partners. The public health jurisdiction will retain ownership of any data it contributes to its exclusive secure space within BioSense `nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:"Syndromic Surveillance", `operatingSystemPlatform`:"", `operationalStatus`:"Program on-going", `overallCapability`:"national syndromic surveillance and situation awareness", `patientTrackingCapability`:"", `purpose`:"The BioSense Program, renamed the National Syndromic Surveillance Program in 2014,  was created by Congressional mandate as a component of the Public Health Security and Bioterrorism Preparedness and Response Act of 2002. The Program was developed and launched by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) in 2003. The information technology component of the Program, the National Syndromic Surveillance Platform (formerly the BioSense platform), is a near real-time surveillance system that receives and processes electronic healthcare encounter data and provides automated and ad hoc syndromic surveillance analysis services. Data sources provide healthcare visit-generated chief complaints, final diagnosis codes, procedure codes, clinical laboratory, pharmacy prescription, and patient demographic data from participating facilities. Healthcare-based data sources include hospital emergency departments, United States Department of Defense (DoD) medical treatment facilities, and Veterans Affairs (VA) outpatient hospitals and clinics nationwide. The BioSense Program also receives pharmacy data from a private sector health information exchange firm and laboratory data from national level private sector clinical laboratories. In 2012, BioSense Program transitioned from a CDC-based hardware platform to an external cloud-based server platform in compliance with the Federal Information Security Management Act. In 2014, enhancements to improve and enhance data processing services and analytic application resources were undertaken, including the deployment of the ESSENCE syndromic surveillance application and SAS statistical software services, with expectations for these services to become available to end users in late 2015.  The National Syndromic Surveillance Program receives guidance from the BioSense Governance Group, a consortium of state/local health departments and partner organizations. The Association of State and Territorial Health Officials (ASTHO) is funded through a cooperative agreement to facilitate the BioSense Governance Group and to contract with the Amazon Web Services (AWS) Cloud vendor for the hardware infrastructure to support the National Syndromic Surveillance Platform. Utilization of the National Syndromic Surveillance Platform is offered to state, local, and territorial health jurisdictions on a voluntary basis, and the National Syndromic Surveillance Program funds state/local-based syndromic surveillance efforts via cooperative agreements. The Platform provides users with an exclusive secure space for posting, receiving, controlling, analyzing, and sharing their public health surveillance information with other public health jurisdictions, CDC, or other public health partners. Each public health jurisdiction administers access rights to data contributed from their respective jurisdiction, controlling who can see the information, and at what level of aggregation. In order to facilitate and encourage data and information sharing, the National Syndromic Surveillance Program, through the ASTHO cooperative agreement, funds and coordinates a Community of Practice for state/local syndromic surveillance staff, and supports HHS Regional Data Sharing Workshops to encourage and enhance the utilization of syndromic surveillance activities across jurisdictional boundaries.", `rels`:"[{\"aid\":\"P3\",\"aname\":\"BioSense Program\",\"bid\":\"O84\",\"bname\":\"Division of Health Informatics and Surveillance\",\"reltype\":\"OVERSEES\",\"startid\":\"O84\",\"endid\":\"P3\",\"startname\":\"Division of Health Informatics and Surveillance\",\"endname\":\"BioSense Program\",\"reldesc\":\"n/a\",\"relid\":1428671110799},{\"aid\":\"P3\",\"aname\":\"BioSense Program\",\"bid\":\"SS15\",\"bname\":\"BioSense Surveillance System\",\"reltype\":\"IS_A_COMPONENT/PART_OF\",\"startid\":\"SS15\",\"endid\":\"P3\",\"startname\":\"BioSense Surveillance System\",\"endname\":\"BioSense Program\",\"reldesc\":\"n/a\",\"relid\":1428671110801}]", `reportFrequency`:"near real time data feeds", `shortName`:"NSSP", `specialPopulations`:"Hospital emergency room patients", `startDate`:"March 2003", `startDateGeneration`:"2003", `state`:"", `surveillanceDomain`:"National, state, local", `surveillanceType`:"Syndromic Surviellance program", `webResource`:"http://www.cdc.gov/BioSense/"})

NHANES is a series of ongoing, nationally-representative, cross-sectional, household surveys assessing the health and nutritional status of adults and children in the United States.   Since 1999, NHANES has included chlamydia screening; gonorrhea screening was included from 1999-2008. NJTP is a vocational program targeting socio-economically disadvantaged men and women aged 16-24 years. NJTP participants are screened for chlamydia and gonorrhea at program entrance. SSuN is a sentinel surveillance network of local STD surveillance systems following common protocols, providing information on patients tested and diagnosed with STDs. create (_2798:`Program` {`Notes`:"", `ageFormat`:"", `applicationPlatform`:"", `applicationSolutionType`:"", `avrCapability`:"", `city`:"", `conditionsUnderSurveillance`:"", `contactEmail`:"", `contactName`:"", `contactPhone`:"", `dataPayloadFormat`:"", `dataPayloadTransmissionType`:"", `dataProviders-Electronic`:"Public Laboratories, Private Laboratories , Local Health Departments, State / Territorial Health Departments, Schools / Universities, Veterinarians", `dataProviders-Manual`:"Public Laboratories, Private Laboratories , Local Health Departments, State / Territorial Health Departments, Schools / Universities, Veterinarians", `dataRecipients-Electronic`:"Federal Government Agencies", `dataRecipients-Manual`:"", `databaseTechnology`:"", `evaluationDate`:"", `evaluationDetails`:"", `fullName`:"Emerging Infections Program", `fundingLevels`:"", `fundingSource`:"", `geographicCoverageArea`:"", `id`:"P8", `informationValidated`:"No", `informationValidatedBy`:"", `informationValidatedOn`:"", `lastUpdated`:"", `lastUpdatedBy`:"", `name`:"Emerging Infections Program", `nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:"", `operatingSystemPlatform`:"", `operationalStatus`:"Fully Operational and Implemented", `overallCapability`:"", `patientTrackingCapability`:"", `purpose`:"EIP is a major cooperative agreement program that supports a network of 10 state health departments (CA, CO, CT, GA, MD, MN, NM, NY, OR, TN) and their collaborators in local health departments, academic institutions, other federal agencies, and public health and clinical laboratories. EIP also supports infection control professionals and healthcare providers. The EIP aims to prevent and control infectious diseases by providing the highest quality scientific information to monitor emerging problems, evaluate public health interventions, transfer what is learned to the public health community, and inform policy. The EIP network aims to be a national resource for surveillance, prevention, and control of emerging infectious diseases. EIP activities  beyond the routine functions of health departments in ways that allow important public health questions to be answered by addressing the most important issues in infectious diseases and selecting projects that the EIP network is particularly suited to investigate, by maintaining sufficient flexibility for emergency response and addressing new problems as they arise by developing, evaluating, and ultimately transferring what is learned to public health agencies, by incorporating training as a key function of EIP activities, and by giving high priority to projects that lead directly to the prevention of disease. Over the years EIP has made important contributions to a variety of key issues in infectious diseases and public health.", `reportFrequency`:"", `shortName`:"EIP", `specialPopulations`:"", `startDate`:"", `startDateGeneration`:"1995", `state`:"", `surveillanceDomain`:"", `surveillanceType`:"", `webResource`:"http://www.cdc.gov/ncpdcid/deiss/eip/index.html"})

create (_2808:`Program` {`Notes`:"", `ageFormat`:"", `applicationPlatform`:"", `applicationSolutionType`:"", `avrCapability`:"", `city`:"", `conditionsUnderSurveillance`:"", `contactEmail`:"", `contactName`:"", `contactPhone`:"", `dataPayloadFormat`:"", `dataPayloadTransmissionType`:"", `dataProviders-Electronic`:"International Partners, Healthcare Providers, Public Laboratories, Private Laboratories , Schools / Universities", `dataProviders-Manual`:"International Partners, Healthcare Providers, Public Laboratories, Private Laboratories , Schools / Universities", `dataRecipients-Electronic`:"", `dataRecipients-Manual`:"", `databaseTechnology`:"", `evaluationDate`:"", `evaluationDetails`:"", `fullName`:"HIV Drug Resistance", `fundingLevels`:"", `fundingSource`:"", `geographicCoverageArea`:"", `id`:"P18", `informationValidated`:"No", `informationValidatedBy`:"", `informationValidatedOn`:"", `lastUpdated`:"", `lastUpdatedBy`:"", `name`:"HIV Drug Resistance", `nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:"", `operatingSystemPlatform`:"", `operationalStatus`:"Fully Operational and Implemented", `overallCapability`:"", `patientTrackingCapability`:"", `purpose`:"Surveillance of transmitted HIV drug resistance (HIVDR) and HIVDR emerging during treatment and also of antiretroviral treatment (ART) program factors associated with the emergence/prevention of HIVDR during treatment. Countries form HIVDR working groups generally based at the Ministry of Health. There are five surveillance elements: 1. HIVDR Early Warning Indicators (EWI) -- all ART sites, or representative ART sites, are surveyed annually for factors associated with HIVDR emergence/prevention: A. ART prescribing practices; B. Percentage of patients lost to follow-up after one year following ART start C. Retention on first-line ART at one year; D. Percentage of ART patients picking up their drugs on-time; E. Percentage of ART patients keeping their appointments on time F. Percentage of months in which there are no ART drug stock-outs. Sample size is calculated based on numbers of ART patients at the site. Targets are recommended; countries may select more stringent targets. 2. Monitoring of HIVDR prevention and associated factors at sentinel ART sites: HIVDR working groups select three - 15 sentinel sites annually and do baseline genotypes and endpoint genotypes on patients starting ART, and abstract other information from medical records associated with HIVDR prevention. 3. HIVDR transmission surveys: These surveys are each focused in one geographic area of the country and use a binominal sequential sampling technique which classifies prevalence of transmitted drug resistance for each of the three ART drug classes used in resource-limited countries as above or below two thresholds: 5% and 15%. 4. Cross-sectional surveys: A representative cross-section of ART patients on first-line ART are surveyed for viral load, and if the viral load is detectable (=ART failure), the specimen is genotyped to evaluate the resistance pattern. 5. Pediatric surveillance of initial HIVDR in children < =18 months of age: Remnant dried blood spots used for pediatric HIV diagnosis are genotyped for children who are HIV-positive, prevention-of-mother to child transmission (PMTCT) information is collected (which regimens received by child and mother) to evaluate resistance patterns associated with PMTCT and also for those children whose PMTCT status is recorded as \"unknown\". Information is used for public health action to change ART program practices at site and national level. The program also includes HIVDR prevention elements (training), a database into which survey data can be entered, a lab training and accreditation system for surveillance genotyping.", `reportFrequency`:"", `shortName`:"", `specialPopulations`:"", `startDate`:"", `startDateGeneration`:"2005", `state`:"", `surveillanceDomain`:"", `surveillanceType`:"", `webResource`:"http://www.who.int/hiv/topics/drugresistance/en/index.html"})

The breastfeeding questions were modified in 2004 and 2006 based on cognitive testing of the questions. In the past, breastfeeding data were presented based on the year in which the data collection occurred. For example, the 2005 NIS was conducted in 2005 but the percentage of children reportedly breastfed at birth, six months, and 12 months, represented children born between February 2002 and May 2004. The VSD project was established in 1990 to monitor immunization safety and address the gaps in scientific knowledge about rare and serious adverse events following immunization. The VSD project includes a large linked database that uses administrative data sources at each MCO. Each participating site gathers data on vaccination (vaccine type, date of vaccination, concurrent vaccinations), medical outcomes (outpatient visits, inpatient visits, urgent care visits), birth data, and census data. The VSD project allows for planned immunization safety studies as well as timely investigations of hypotheses that arise from review of medical literature, reports to the Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS), changes in immunization schedules, or the introduction of new vaccines. The objectives of VSD are to conduct population based research on immunization safety questions; to evaluate immunization safety hypotheses that arise from medical literature, passive surveillance systems, adjustments to immunization schedules, and introduction of new vaccines; to guide national immunization policy decisions; and to partner with healthcare providers, public health officials, and others to ensure the public has the best available information regarding the risks and benefits of immunizations.", `reportFrequency`:"", `shortName`:"VSD", `specialPopulations`:"", `startDate`:"", `startDateGeneration`:"1991", `state`:"", `surveillanceDomain`:"", `surveillanceType`:"", `webResource`:"http://www.cdc.gov/vaccinesafety/Activities/VSD.html"})

ABCs is an active laboratory- and population-based surveillance system for invasive bacterial pathogens of public health importance. For each case of invasive disease in the surveillance population, a case report form with basic demographic information is completed and bacterial isolates are sent to CDC and other reference laboratories for additional laboratory evaluation. ABCs also provides an infrastructure for further public health research, including special studies aiming at identifying risk factors for disease, post-licensure evaluation of vaccine efficacy and monitoring effectiveness of prevention policies.  ABCs was initially established in four states in 1995. It currently operates among 10 EIP sites across the United States, representing a population of approximately 42 million persons. At this time, ABCs conducts surveillance for six pathogens: group A and group B Streptococcus (GAS, GBS), Haemophilus influenzae, Neisseria meningitidis, Streptococcus pneumoniae, and methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA). Additionally, surveillance for legionellosis and enhanced surveillance for pertussis has been ongoing since 2011. The program objective is to build state capacity to initiate, expand, or improve adult blood lead surveillance programs which can accurately measure trends in adult blood lead levels and which can effectively intervene to prevent lead over-exposures.   The public health objective of the ABLES program is identical to the Occupational Safety and Health objective 7 in Healthy People 2020, which is to reduce the rate of adults (age 16 or older) who have blood lead levels (BLL) equal or greater than ten micrograms per deciliter (BLLs ≥10 µg/dL). To identify these cases and acquire detailed data on them, staff of the Alaska Pacific Regional Office (APRO), formerly known as the Alaska Field Station, collect information from local, state and federal sources, other professional contacts and news media. BRFSS collects data in all 50 states as well as the District of Columbia and three U.S. territories. BRFSS completes more than 400,000 adult interviews each year, making it the largest continuously conducted health survey system in the world.   BRFSS collects state data about U.S. residents regarding their health-related risk behaviors and events, chronic health conditions, and use of preventive services. BRFSS also collects data on important emerging health issues such as vaccine shortage and influenza-like illness. For example, since September 2009, federal, state, and local health agencies have used BRFSS to monitor the prevalence rates of influenza-like illness to help with pandemic planning. Interviewers administer the annual BRFSS surveys continuously through the year", `reportFrequency`:"", `shortName`:"BRFSS", `specialPopulations`:"", `startDate`:"", `startDateGeneration`:"1984", `state`:"", `surveillanceDomain`:"", `surveillanceType`:"", `webResource`:"http://www.cdc.gov/BRFSS/"})
create (_2852:`SurveillanceSystem` {`CR_DATE_CREATED`:1428671078869, `CR_DATE_EDITED`:"", `CR_DATE_EXECUTED`:1428687754186, `CR_NODE_TYPE`:"SurveillanceSystem", `CR_PREVIOUS`:"{\"name\":\"BioSense Surveillance System\",\"id\":\"SS15\",\"purpose\":\"The BioSense program is a public health surveillance system that increases the ability of health officials at local, state, and national levels to efficiently, rapidly and collaboratively monitor and respond to harmful health effects of exposure to disease or hazardous conditions.  BioSense provides public health officials a common electronic health information system with standardized tools and procedures for rapidly collecting, sharing, and evaluating information.  With BioSense, health officials can exchange information faster, improve their common awareness of health threats over time and across regional boundaries, and better coordinate investigations and community actions to protect health.  BioSense 2.0 is the latest version of the BioSense system. It is a streamlined collaborative data-exchange system that enables its users, who have agreed to share health-related data, to track health issues as they develop and to share this information quickly with other public health jurisdictions in the system.  BioSense 2.0 provides a mechanism to collect and share information on emergency department visits, hospitalizations, and other health related data from multiple sources, including the Department of Veterans Affairs (VA), the Department of Defense (DoD), and civilian hospitals from around the country.   Analysis of these data provides insight into the health of communities and the country. Such data are vital to guide decision making and actions by public health agencies at all levels. BioSense 2.0 was developed and is governed through an active collaboration of CDC, state and local health departments, and other public health partners. `operatingSystemPlatform`:"Linux, Microsoft Windows", `operationalStatus`:"Fully Operational and Implemented", `overallCapability`:"Syndromic surviellance", `patientTrackingCapability`:"Patient ID protected visit tracking", `purpose`:"The National Syndromic Surveillance Program, formerly known as BioSense, is a public health surveillance program that enhances the ability of health officials at local, state, and national levels to efficiently, rapidly and collaboratively identify, characterize, monitor, and respond to harmful health effects of exposure to disease or hazardous conditions utilizing health care services data.  The BioSense - National Syndromic Surveillance Platform is a software platform that provides public health officials a common health information exchange platform with standardized syndromic surveillance data analysis and visualization tools and procedures for rapidly acquiring, analyzing, sharing, and evaluating data and information. The platform provides a mechanism to acquire data on emergency department visits, ambulatory care visits, and other health services related data from multiple sources, including the Department of Veterans Affairs (VA), the Department of Defense (DoD), and civilian hospitals from around the country.   Analysis of these data provides insight into the health status of communities and the country, and information derived from analyses of these data is vital to guide decision making and actions by public health agencies at the local, state, and national level.  State/local health departments who have agreed to share health-related data can utilize the BioSense platform to efficiently exchange syndromic surveillance data and information to track health-related issues as they emerge, and to collaborate with other public health jurisdictions utilizing the system. This allows common situation awareness of health threats over time and across regional boundaries, and supports improved coordination of investigations and community actions to respond to events and protect health. The BioSense - National Syndromic Surveillance System is developed and governed through an active collaboration of CDC, state and local health departments, and other public health partners.", create (_2863:`SurveillanceSystem` {`Notes`:"", `ageFormat`:"", `applicationPlatform`:"", `applicationSolutionType`:"", `avrCapability`:"", `city`:"", `conditionsUnderSurveillance`:"", `contactEmail`:"", `contactName`:"", `contactPhone`:"", `dataPayloadFormat`:"", `dataPayloadTransmissionType`:"", `dataProvidersElectronic`:"Healthcare Providers, Local Health Departments, State / Territorial Health Departments", `dataProvidersManual`:"Healthcare Providers, Local Health Departments, State / Territorial Health Departments", `dataRecipientsElectronic`:"State / Territorial Health Departments", `dataRecipientsManual`:"", `databaseTechnology`:"", `evaluationDate`:"", `evaluationDetails`:"", `fullName`:"", `fundingLevels`:"", `fundingSource`:"", `geographicCoverageArea`:"", `id`:"SS26", `informationValidated`:"No", `informationValidatedBy`:"", `informationValidatedOn`:"", `lastUpdated`:"", `lastUpdatedBy`:"", `name`:"Countermeasure Tracking Systems", `nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:"", `operatingSystemPlatform`:"", `operationalStatus`:"Partially Operational and Implemented", `overallCapability`:"", `patientTrackingCapability`:"", `purpose`:"CTS consists of multiple interoperating components which enhance the capacity of federal, state, and local public health agencies to track and manage medical and non-medical inventory and usage to support both daily operations and all-hazards events. The four system components interoperate to improve communications and event response efficiency while still functioning independently, recognizing the unique requirements and use cases for each system. In support of close communication and linkage among the components, all four system components have a similar “look and feel” and use the same security mechanism which allows a seamless transition between systems, enhancing ease of use and supporting just-in-time training. Collectively, the data consolidated from these systems can show population coverage, numbers of untreated individuals, drug and equipment shortages, need for resupply and more. The Web-based applications are deployed centrally at CDC and use the CDC’s secure data access method for security. They are available free of charge to users.  Overview of System Components:  Inventory Management and Tracking System (IMATS)-  The IMATS solution provides state and local public health providers with a tool to track medical and non-medical countermeasure inventory and supplies during daily operations or an event. The solution tracks quantities of inventory, monitors reorder thresholds, and facilitates warehouse operations including receiving, staging, and storing of inventory.  Communications Portal (CP)-  The Communications Portal is a content management system that consolidates important event response information in one place ensuring efficient communications during an event. Such information may include Emergency Use Authorization (EUA) and Investigational New Drug (IND) information, lot recalls, and other related information and materials.  Countermeasure and Response Administration (CRA)-  CRA is an emergency preparedness and response asset useful for any event involving vaccine doses administered tracking, pharmaceuticals and medical materiel dispensing, or implementation of social distancing measures. CRA supports analysis of pharmaceutical safety, coverage, and effectiveness during an event which improves patient outcomes. CRA is a flexible all-hazards system that reduces the need for development of new applications each time there is a new event.  Countermeasure Inventory Tracking (CIT) Dashboard-  The CIT Dashboard (a.k.a. the Countermeasure Supply Chain Dashboard) is a situational awareness tool used by the Division of Strategic National Stockpile to construct a nationwide inventory supply picture. The CIT Dashboard consolidates project area inventory data reported through CRA with data from the commercial drug sector. This consolidated data forms a complete inventory supply picture which provides situational awareness during an event. Additionally, farming is one of the few industries in which family members (who often share the work and live on the premises) are also at risk for fatal and nonfatal injuries.  Youth who live on, work on, or visit farms in the United States (U.S.) have been identified as a special population at high risk for non-fatal and fatal injuries. Since 1996, NIOSH has conducted the Childhood Agricultural Injury Prevention Initiative to promote the reduction of injuries and fatalities to youth on farms in the U.S. A major component of this initiative is the development of an ongoing surveillance program to track the magnitude of non-fatal injuries occurring to all youth exposed to farm hazards.  An initial step in the development of the surveillance program was the completion of the Childhood Agricultural Injury Survey (CAIS) first conducted in 1999 for the calendar year 1998. NIOSH collaborated with the U.S. Department of Agriculture’s National Agricultural Statistics Service (USDA-NASS) to conduct this survey.  In 1990, Congress directed NIOSH to develop an extensive agricultural safety and health program to address the high risks of injuries and illnesses experienced by workers and families in agriculture. One component of this program was the development of an ongoing surveillance program to track the magnitude of nonfatal injuries occurring to adults working in agriculture.  An initial step in the development of the surveillance program was the completion of the Occupational Injury Surveillance of Production Agriculture (OISPA) survey.  This survey, first conducted for the calendar year 2001, was designed to produce national and regional estimates of the number of adults 20 years of age and older working on farms and the number of occupational injuries that these workers incur.  NIOSH collaborated with the US Department of Agriculture’s National Agricultural Statistics Service (USDA-NASS) to conduct the initial survey, as well as additional OISPA surveys for calendar years 2004 and 2009. Hundreds of nongovernmental organizations (NGOs) established health-care clinics in camps of internally displaced persons (IDPs).   To monitor conditions of outbreak potential identified at NGO camp clinics, on February 18, the Haiti Ministry of Public Health and Population (MSPP), the Pan-American Health Organization (PAHO), and CDC implemented the IDP Surveillance System (IDPSS).  The Inter-Agency Standing Committee (IASC) \"cluster approach\" (1) was used to coordinate the Haiti humanitarian response. One of 11 clusters, the Global Health Cluster (GHC), builds global capacity, whereas the country-level cluster (in this case, the Haitian Health Cluster [HHC], led by PAHO) responds locally. During the Haiti response, HHC engaged NGOs serving large camps, established IDPSS, followed trends of reportable conditions, undertook epidemiologic and laboratory investigations, and fostered implementation of control measures. Listeria infections (listeriosis) are nationally notifiable. Nearly all cases of listeriosis in persons who are not infants result from eating food contaminated with L. monocytogenes; newborn infants can develop listeriosis if their mother ate contaminated food during pregnancy.    The Listeria Initiative is an enhanced surveillance system that collects reports of laboratory-confirmed cases of human listeriosis in the United States. Demographic, clinical, laboratory, and epidemiologic data are collected using a standardized, extended questionnaire. The Listeria Initiative was piloted in the Foodborne Diseases Active Surveillance Network (FoodNet) in 2004 and implemented nationwide in 2005. At the time, no system in the U.S. collected nationally representative data on these practices. The Expert Panel’s recommendation was to establish an ongoing, national system to monitor and evaluate hospital practices related to breastfeeding among all facilities that routinely provide intrapartum care in the U.S.  In 2007, CDC administered the first national survey of maternity practices related to breastfeeding, known as the mPINC survey. It was administered to every facility in the U.S. that routinely provides maternity care services, and was to be completed by a key informant on behalf of his or her institution in their capacity as the person most knowledgeable about the relevant practices. The information is obtained directly from farm workers through face-to-face interviews. Since 1988, when the survey began, nearly 50,000 workers have been interviewed. The NAWS is performed under contract to the Department of Labor and its information is made available to the public through periodic research reports and a public use data set. Numerous Federal government agencies utilize NAWS findings for a multitude of purposes, including occupational injury and health surveillance, estimating the need for services, allocating program dollars to areas of greatest need, and program design and evaluation. The survey samples crop workers in three cycles each year to reflect the seasonality of agricultural production and employment. Workers are located at their farm job sites. During the initial contact, arrangements are made to interview the respondent at home or at another location convenient to the respondent. Depending on the information needs and resources of the various Federal agencies that use NAWS data, between 1,500 and 4,000 workers are interviewed each year.", `reportFrequency`:"", `shortName`:"NAWS", `specialPopulations`:"", `startDate`:"", `startDateGeneration`:"1999", `state`:"", `surveillanceDomain`:"", `surveillanceType`:"", `webResource`:"http://www.doleta.gov/agworker/naws.cfm"})

create (_2912:`SurveillanceSystem` {`Notes`:"", `ageFormat`:"", `applicationPlatform`:"", `applicationSolutionType`:"", `avrCapability`:"", `city`:"", `conditionsUnderSurveillance`:"", `contactEmail`:"", `contactName`:"", `contactPhone`:"", `dataPayloadFormat`:"", `dataPayloadTransmissionType`:"", `dataProvidersElectronic`:"Local Health Departments, State / Territorial Health Departments", `dataProvidersManual`:"", `dataRecipientsElectronic`:"Federal Government Agencies, Members Of General Public, State / Territorial Health Departments", `dataRecipientsManual`:"", `databaseTechnology`:"", `evaluationDate`:"", `evaluationDetails`:"", `fullName`:"", `fundingLevels`:"", `fundingSource`:"", `geographicCoverageArea`:"", `id`:"SS83", `informationValidated`:"No", `informationValidatedBy`:"", `informationValidatedOn`:"", `lastUpdated`:"", `lastUpdatedBy`:"", `name`:"National Arboviral Surveillance System", `nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:"", `operatingSystemPlatform`:"", `operationalStatus`:"Fully Operational and Implemented", `overallCapability`:"", `patientTrackingCapability`:"", `purpose`:"ArboNET is a national arboviral surveillance system managed by CDC and state health departments. In addition to human disease, ArboNET maintains data on arboviral infections among presumptive viremic blood donors, veterinary disease cases, mosquitoes, dead birds, and sentinel animals.  As with other national surveillance data, ArboNET data have several limitations that should be considered in analysis, interpretation, and reporting:  1.  ArboNET is a passive surveillance system. It is dependent on clinicians considering the diagnosis of an arboviral disease and obtaining the appropriate diagnostic test, and reporting of laboratory-confirmed cases to public health authorities. Diagnosis and reporting are incomplete, and the incidence of arboviral diseases is underestimated.   2.  Reported neuroinvasive disease cases are considered the most accurate indicator of arboviral activity in humans because of the substantial associated morbidity. In contrast, reported cases of nonneuroinvasive arboviral disease are more likely to be affected by disease awareness and healthcare-seek­ing behavior in different communities and by the availability and specificity of laboratory tests performed. Surveillance data for nonneuroinvasive disease should be interpreted with cau­tion and generally should not be used to make comparisons between geographic areas or over time.   3.  Provisional ArboNET data are provided to help track recent arboviral disease activity. However, these data may change substantially before they are finalized. Provisional data from the current year should not be combined with or compared to final data from previous years. Throughout the world, biomonitoring has become the standard for assessing people's exposure to toxic substances as well as for responding to serious environmental public health problems. Rather than estimating how much of a substance gets into people from measured environmental concentrations, our scientists have taken out the guesswork by measuring levels of chemicals that actually are in people's bodies. And they do so with precision, speed, and pinpoint accuracy, measuring many chemicals in a very small amount—often a teaspoon or less—of blood or urine. NBP currently measures more than 450 environmental chemicals and nutritional indicators in people. All of the methods used have been published in peer-reviewed journals so that other laboratories can use them. create (_2923:`SurveillanceSystem` {`CR_DATE_CREATED`:1429034046752, `CR_DATE_EDITED`:"", `CR_DATE_EXECUTED`:1429034080598, `CR_NODE_TYPE`:"SurveillanceSystem", `CR_PREVIOUS`:"{\"name\":\"National HealthCare Safety Network\",\"id\":\"SS94\",\"purpose\":\"NHSN is a web-based information system designed for use by CDC and partners as a resource for surveillance and improvement of patient and healthcare personnel safety. The principle goal of NHSN are to improve safety by creating and disseminating knowledge necessary to detect and respond to current and emerging healthcare safety threats. Healthcare-associated infections and antimicrobial resistance are major problems in US healthcare institutions. In hospitals alone, nearly 2 million patients acquire infections that contribute to more than 88,000 deaths and cost more than $4.5 billion annually. Healthcare personnel are also at risk of acquiring infection while performing duties. NHSN today, is used for infection control, healthcare worker safety, blood safety, process-of-care measurement and improvement, prevention research, mandatory public reporting and public health surveillance. NHSN has been designated the system to use by facilities electing to participate in the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) Healthcare Associated Infection (HAI) Inpatient Quality Reporting (IQR) Program, ESRD Quality Incentive Program (QIP), Long Term Care Hospital Quality Reporting (LTCHQR) Program, Inpatient Rehabilitation Facility Quality Reporting Program, PPS-Exempt Cancer Hospital Quality Reporting (PCHQR) Program and Ambulatory Surgery Centers Quality Reporting Program. As part of each program, HAI events are reported to NHSN and shared with CMS. The partnership with CMS is a step toward greater transparency of HAI data and also toward stronger accountability within the US healthcare system. It also highlights the importance of strong facility-level support for infection prevention programs and professionals.  Currently there are 17,000 healthcare facilities enrolled with an estimated target of an additional 2000 within calendar year 2015. Functionally, NHSN supports a manual data entry and uses pre-existing electronic data from electronic health records (EHR) and other healthcare information systems using Health Level 7 (HL7) balloted and standardized Clinical Document Architecture (CDA) documents for automated data entry. The development aspects of the project primarily supports and maintains the operations of the system and user support while integrating new feature and functionality deemed necessary by CDC’s SB/DHQP `patientTrackingCapability`:"", `purpose`:"NHSN is a web-based information system designed for use by CDC and partners as a resource for surveillance and improvement of patient and healthcare personnel safety. The principle goal of NHSN are to improve safety by creating and disseminating knowledge necessary to detect and respond to current and emerging healthcare safety threats. Healthcare-associated infections and antimicrobial resistance are major problems in US healthcare institutions. In hospitals alone, nearly 2 million patients acquire infections that contribute to more than 88,000 deaths and cost more than $4.5 billion annually. Healthcare personnel are also at risk of acquiring infection while performing duties. NHSN today, is used for infection control, healthcare worker safety, blood safety, process-of-care measurement and improvement, prevention research, mandatory public reporting and public health surveillance. NHSN has been designated the system to use by facilities electing to participate in the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) Healthcare Associated Infection (HAI) Inpatient Quality Reporting (IQR) Program, ESRD Quality Incentive Program (QIP), Long Term Care Hospital Quality Reporting (LTCHQR) Program, Inpatient Rehabilitation Facility Quality Reporting Program, PPS-Exempt Cancer Hospital Quality Reporting (PCHQR) Program and Ambulatory Surgery Centers Quality Reporting Program. As part of each program, HAI events are reported to NHSN and shared with CMS. The partnership with CMS is a step toward greater transparency of HAI data and also toward stronger accountability within the US healthcare system. It also highlights the importance of strong facility-level support for infection prevention programs and professionals.  Currently there are 17,000 healthcare facilities enrolled with an estimated target of an additional 2000 within calendar year 2015. Functionally, NHSN supports a manual data entry and uses pre-existing electronic data from electronic health records (EHR) and other healthcare information systems using Health Level 7 (HL7) balloted and standardized Clinical Document Architecture (CDA) documents for automated data entry. The development aspects of the project primarily supports and maintains the operations of the system and user support while integrating new feature and functionality deemed necessary by CDC’s SB/DHQP The overall strategy for NHBS involves conducting rotating 12 month cycles of surveillance in three different populations at high risk for HIV: men who have sex with men (MSM), injection drug users (IDU) and heterosexuals at high risk of HIV infection (HET). Surveillance will be conducted with these three groups in up to 25 Metropolitan Statistical Areas (MSA) over time; these MSA were chosen as they had high AIDS prevalence. Grantees for NHBS include state and directly-funded city health departments; many grantees contract with local health departments, universities, or community-based organizations to conduct NHBS activities. All NHBS project areas use a standardized, anonymous questionnaire for each cycle of the survey. The questionnaire collects information about behavioral risks for HIV, HIV testing and exposure to and use of prevention services. The survey is administered by trained interviewers using handheld computers. The same basic eligibility criteria are used in each of the project areas: at least 18 years of age and a resident of the MSA. A minimum of 500 eligible persons from each MSA are interviewed each cycle. The NIS is a list-assisted random-digit-dialing telephone survey followed by a mailed survey to children’s immunization providers that began data collection in April 1994 to monitor childhood vaccination coverage at national, state and selected local areas for children aged 19-35 months. Cellular telephones were included in the survey beginning in 2011. Starting in 2008, NIS-Teen was expanded to provide vaccination coverage estimates at state and selected local levels. The NIS and NIS-Teen also collect detailed insurance status data enabling the estimation of the percentage of children in the United States eligible for the Vaccines for Children (VFC) program. The sampling frame for the NIS also provides an efficient approach for conducting other surveys managed by NCHS, the State and Local Area Integrated Telephone Survey (SLAITS). create (_2934:`SurveillanceSystem` {`Notes`:"", `ageFormat`:"", `applicationPlatform`:"", `applicationSolutionType`:"", `avrCapability`:"", `city`:"", `conditionsUnderSurveillance`:"", `contactEmail`:"", `contactName`:"", `contactPhone`:"", `dataPayloadFormat`:"", `dataPayloadTransmissionType`:"", `dataProvidersElectronic`:"Healthcare Providers", `dataProvidersManual`:"Members Of General Public", `dataRecipientsElectronic`:"Federal Government Agencies, Local Health Departments, State / Territorial Health Departments", `dataRecipientsManual`:"", `databaseTechnology`:"", `evaluationDate`:"", `evaluationDetails`:"", `fullName`:"", `fundingLevels`:"", `fundingSource`:"", `geographicCoverageArea`:"", `id`:"SS105", `informationValidated`:"No", `informationValidatedBy`:"", `informationValidatedOn`:"", `lastUpdated`:"", `lastUpdatedBy`:"", `name`:"National Poison Data System", `nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:"", `operatingSystemPlatform`:"", `operationalStatus`:"Fully Operational and Implemented", `overallCapability`:"", `patientTrackingCapability`:"", `purpose`:"NPDS surveillance activities are the cornerstone of the National Center for Environmental Health’s (NCEH) National Chemical and Radiological Surveillance Program. The primary objective of NCEH’s National Chemical and Radiological Surveillance Program is to provide CDC with a national surveillance capability to better detect and respond to chemical, environmental, drug, foodborne, biological and radiological exposures and illnesses of potential public health significance. On average, every 24 minutes, 57 regional Poison Centers (PCs) upload data collected from calls made to their facilities to the national poison center reporting database and system known as the National Poison Data System or NPDS. NPDS is used as a surveillance system for the analysis, visualization, and reporting of PC data in cooperation with NCEH.  Since 2001, CDC and American Association of Poison Control Centers (AAPCC) have developed methods to use NPDS data for near, real-time surveillance of exposures to hazardous substances of potential public health significance. Automated algorithms run continuously in NPDS and identify data anomalies which are then reviewed by members of the NPDS Surveillance Team to gauge their public health significance and to ensure the appropriate public health authorities are notified. CDC currently uses NPDS to: improve national surveillance for chemical, environmental, drug, foodborne, biological and radiological exposures and illness of potential public health significance; identify early markers of chemical, environmental, drug, foodborne, biological and radiological events in order to provide an effective and rapid public heath response; and to identify and track exposures and cases of illness during an emerging or known public health threat.NPDS is wholly owned and operated by the American Association of Poison Control Centers (AAPCC).", `reportFrequency`:"", `shortName`:"NPDS", `specialPopulations`:"", `startDate`:"", `startDateGeneration`:"2000", `state`:"", `surveillanceDomain`:"", `surveillanceType`:"", `webResource`:"http://www.aapcc.org/"})

voluntary and secure electronic occupational safety and health surveillance system developed by the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH), part of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). OHSN currently focuses on occupational safety and health issues in the Healthcare Sector, though it may expand to other industry sectors in the future. The first three modules address traumatic injury risks among healthcare personnel. With OHSN, healthcare facilities can submit the occupational health data they already collect to track their rates and to benchmark against other OHSN participants. PDSS is used for surveillance of dengue occurrences among residents of Puerto Rico and the USVI, as well as among US returning travelers. The database contains patient information and laboratory results process at the Dengue Branch Laboratory in San Juan. It searches for previous samples from patients, stores data on the samples, and stores clinical and epidemiological information. The data is used for epidemiologic analyses of disease activity in certain periods or locations by Dengue Branch scientists. Sample results are reported to the patients’ health care provider. Summary data of reported suspected cases and laboratory confirmed dengue cases is disseminated to stakeholders in Puerto Rico, for example the Puerto Rico Department of Health, and in the continental US. The data is also sent weekly to ArboNET and reported in the MMWR Weekly Report. Health departments in the 50 states, the District of Columbia, and New York City provide CDC with copies of death certificates and available linked outcome records (i.e., birth certificates or fetal death certificates) of all deaths occurring during or within 1 year of pregnancy. State maternal mortality review committees, the media, and individual providers report a limited number of deaths not otherwise identified. Death certificates and relevant birth or fetal death certificates are reviewed by clinically experienced epidemiologists at CDC to determine the cause of death and outcome of the pregnancy, associated medical conditions and whether they are pregnancy-related (i.e., have a temporal and causal relationship to pregnancy). create (_2959:`SurveillanceSystem` {`Notes`:"", `ageFormat`:"", `applicationPlatform`:"", `applicationSolutionType`:"", `avrCapability`:"", `city`:"", `conditionsUnderSurveillance`:"", `contactEmail`:"", `contactName`:"", `contactPhone`:"", `dataPayloadFormat`:"", `dataPayloadTransmissionType`:"", `dataProvidersElectronic`:"", `dataProvidersManual`:"Local Health Departments, State / Territorial Health Departments, Tribal Health Departments", `dataRecipientsElectronic`:"", `dataRecipientsManual`:"Local Health Departments, State / Territorial Health Departments, Tribal Health Departments", `databaseTechnology`:"", `evaluationDate`:"", `evaluationDetails`:"", `fullName`:"", `fundingLevels`:"", `fundingSource`:"", `geographicCoverageArea`:"New York City", `id`:"SS130", `informationValidated`:"No", `informationValidatedBy`:"", `informationValidatedOn`:"", `lastUpdated`:"", `lastUpdatedBy`:"", `name`:"Pregnancy Risk Assessment Monitoring System", `nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:"", `operatingSystemPlatform`:"", `operationalStatus`:"Fully Operational and Implemented", `overallCapability`:"", `patientTrackingCapability`:"", `purpose`:"PRAMS, the Pregnancy Risk Assessment Monitoring System, is a surveillance project of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and state health departments. PRAMS collects state-specific, population-based data on maternal attitudes and experiences before, during, and shortly after pregnancy. PRAMS was initiated in 1987 because infant mortality rates were no longer declining as rapidly as they had in prior years. In addition, the incidence of low birth weight infants had changed little in the previous 20 years. Research has indicated that maternal behaviors during pregnancy may influence infant birth weight and mortality rates. The goal of the PRAMS project is to improve the health of mothers and infants by reducing adverse outcomes such as low birth weight, infant mortality and morbidity, and maternal morbidity. PRAMS provides state-specific data for planning and assessing health programs and for describing maternal experiences that may contribute to maternal and infant health. PRAMS provides data for state health officials to use to improve the health of mothers and infants. PRAMS allows CDC and the states to monitor changes in maternal and child health indicators (e.g., unintended pregnancy, prenatal care, breast-feeding, smoking, drinking, infant health). PRAMS enhances information from birth certificates used to plan and review state maternal and infant health programs. The PRAMS sample is chosen from all women who had a live birth recently, so findings can be applied to the state's entire population of women who have recently delivered a live-born infant. PRAMS not only provides state-specific data but also allows comparisons among participating states because the same data collection methods are used in all states.", `reportFrequency`:"", `shortName`:"PRAMS", `specialPopulations`:"", `startDate`:"", `startDateGeneration`:"1988", `state`:"", `surveillanceDomain`:"", `surveillanceType`:"", `webResource`:"http://www.cdc.gov/prams/"})
create (_2960:`SurveillanceSystem` {`Notes`:"", `ageFormat`:"", `applicationPlatform`:"", `applicationSolutionType`:"", `avrCapability`:"", `city`:"", `conditionsUnderSurveillance`:"", `contactEmail`:"", `contactName`:"", `contactPhone`:"", `dataPayloadFormat`:"", `dataPayloadTransmissionType`:"", `dataProvidersElectronic`:"Members Of General Public", `dataProvidersManual`:"Members Of General Public", `dataRecipientsElectronic`:"State / Territorial Health Departments", `dataRecipientsManual`:"", `databaseTechnology`:"", `evaluationDate`:"", `evaluationDetails`:"", `fullName`:"", `fundingLevels`:"", `fundingSource`:"", `geographicCoverageArea`:"", `id`:"SS131", `informationValidated`:"No", `informationValidatedBy`:"", `informationValidatedOn`:"", `lastUpdated`:"", `lastUpdatedBy`:"", `name`:"Public Health Genomics Surveillance - Coordination Activity", `nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:"", `operatingSystemPlatform`:"", `operationalStatus`:"Fully Operational and Implemented", `overallCapability`:"", `patientTrackingCapability`:"", `purpose`:"Assessing the public’s awareness and use of genomic tests and family health history through population-based surveys provides important baseline data, and helps monitors progress toward implementing evidence-based recommendations, including those underlying Healthy People 2020 objectives. Additionally, it contributes to the knowledge base that supports the development and dissemination of appropriate public health messages and educational materials for the general public and health care providers, as well as informing federal and state policy. In 2012, the CDC Office of Public Health Genomics developed a three-tiered framework for classifying genomic tests and family health history based on the availability of scientific evidence and evidence-based recommendations supporting their use. Tier 1 genomic applications are recommended for clinical use by evidence-based panels, based on systematic review of evidence of validity and utility. Tier 2 applications may be useful for informed decision making in clinical practice, based on demonstrated validity, and promising utility.  Tier 3 applications are not ready for clinical use, due to validity or utility not demonstrated, or systematic assessment finding harms outweigh benefits. States are assessing awareness and use of specific Tier 1, 2 and 3 genomic applications using state-added questions in the Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS). Ethical, legal and social issues:  The potential for genetic discrimination is a concern relevant to the increased availability of genetic information associated with the increased use of genetic tests in clinical practice and in the direct-to-consumer market.  The Genetic Information Nondiscrimination Act (GINA) was signed into law in 2008. While GINA is designed to protect against discrimination in health insurance coverage and employment, it does not address other areas where discrimination is possible, such as in life, disability and long-term care insurance. More information is needed on the extent that the general public is aware of protections offered under GINA, and is concerned about the potential for genetic discrimination, since these may prove to be significant factors affecting the uptake of genetic testing. Four questions were added to BRFSS in Michigan, Oregon, Ohio, and Connecticut to collect this information.", `reportFrequency`:"", `shortName`:"", `specialPopulations`:"", `startDate`:"", `startDateGeneration`:"2008", `state`:"", `surveillanceDomain`:"", `surveillanceType`:"", `webResource`:"NULL"})

create (_2962:`SurveillanceSystem` {`Notes`:"", `ageFormat`:"", `applicationPlatform`:"", `applicationSolutionType`:"", `avrCapability`:"", `city`:"", `conditionsUnderSurveillance`:"", `contactEmail`:"", `contactName`:"", `contactPhone`:"", `dataPayloadFormat`:"", `dataPayloadTransmissionType`:"", `dataProvidersElectronic`:"Federal Government Agencies, Public Laboratories, State / Territorial Health Departments", `dataProvidersManual`:"State / Territorial Health Departments", `dataRecipientsElectronic`:"Federal Government Agencies, Public Laboratories, State / Territorial Health Departments", `dataRecipientsManual`:"", `databaseTechnology`:"", `evaluationDate`:"", `evaluationDetails`:"", `fullName`:"", `fundingLevels`:"", `fundingSource`:"", `geographicCoverageArea`:"not specified", `id`:"SS133", `informationValidated`:"No", `informationValidatedBy`:"", `informationValidatedOn`:"", `lastUpdated`:"", `lastUpdatedBy`:"", `name`:"Rabies Surveillance Network", `nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:"", `operatingSystemPlatform`:"", `operationalStatus`:"Partially Operational and Implemented", `overallCapability`:"", `patientTrackingCapability`:"", `purpose`:"The rabies surveillance network (RSN) was established to provide a central repository for accessing rabies surveillance data in the United States by state and local health department personnel as well as federal personnel engaged in rabies prevention and control at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention and US Department of Agriculture / Wildlife Services. RSN represents the combined work of rabies surveillance activity by all 50 states, Puerto Rico, and enhanced surveillance activity by USDA/WS field biologists. The system blends county aggregate case data as well as point data in a dynamic geographic information system that allows for situational awareness of regional intensities and spread of animal rabies. The primary goals of SEARCH are 1) to develop a uniform classification of types of childhood diabetes (no \"gold standard\" definitions of types now exist) 2) to estimate the number of new (incidence) and existing (prevalence) childhood diabetes cases by type, age of the child, sex, and racial or ethnic group 3) to describe the clinical characteristics of different types of diabetes in youth and how they evolved 4) to describe the complications of diabetes in children and adolescents 5) to describe the quality of life of children and adolescents with diabetes. Six U.S. sites collaborate with CDC and NIH on SEARCH. The youth population being studied is provided by the six SEARCH sites and involves more than 5 million, or 6 percent, of all American children aged 0 to 19 years. This will be the largest and most racially and geographically diverse study group ever involved in a youth diabetes study. During the 5-year study period, the SEARCH sites will examine more than 6,000 existing cases of pediatric diabetes and about 800 new cases each year. Data collection began in 2002. With data provided by the SEARCH study, scientists can follow current cases of childhood diabetes to monitor any changes that occur in the type, characteristics, and outcomes of specific cases. The data collection of childhood diabetes cases will provide valuable information to researchers and health care providers in developing appropriate care and treatment protocols that will reduce the likelihood of complications and lessen the burden of diabetes in the daily lives of children and adolescents with diabetes.", `reportFrequency`:"", `shortName`:"Search", `specialPopulations`:"", `startDate`:"", `startDateGeneration`:"2001", `state`:"", `surveillanceDomain`:"", `surveillanceType`:"", `webResource`:"http://www.searchfordiabetes.org/"})

The methods used have been developed using a consensus building process working group with representatives from the Safe States Alliance, the Council of State and Territorial Epidemiologists (CSTE), the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and its National Center for Injury Prevention and Control (NCIPC), and the Society for Advancement of Violence and Injury Research (SAVIR). Methods are fully delineated in the annual State Injury Indicators: Instructions for Preparing Data manuals. In brief, injury hospitalization and emergency department cases are identified from state-based HDD  and ED data using the principal diagnosis (or first-listed ICD-9-CM diagnosis code) with other selective factors. Injury deaths are identified from vital statistics data using the ICD-10 underlying-cause-of-death codes. All multiple-cause-of-death fields are searched for the fatal TBI indicator. For comparison purposes, national rates for the fatality indicators are generated by using the NVSS. National rates for the hospitalization and emergency department visit indicators are generated using the HCUP, NIS, and NEDS.", `reportFrequency`:"", `shortName`:"SII", `specialPopulations`:"", `startDate`:"", `startDateGeneration`:"2004", `state`:"", `surveillanceDomain`:"", `surveillanceType`:"", `webResource`:"http://www.cdc.gov/injury/stateprograms/indicators.html"})

There are approximately 4,200 SUID each year in the United States. About half of these are called Sudden Infant Death Syndrome (SIDS).The SUID CR is a multi-state surveillance system developed to more accurately monitor SUID trends. The purpose of SUID case registry is to collect comprehensive and standardized information about the circumstances and events associated with SUID case; and to improve the quality of SUID data collection systems by developing and maintaining an active surveillance system of all SUID. The SUID Case Registry collects information (including reports from death scene investigations, autopsy, medical and social service records, death and birth certificates) concerning important environmental and physiologic characteristics associated with SUID, as well as information about the completeness of death scene investigations and autopsies that were conducted. The registry builds upon current efforts by the HRSA’s MCHB National Center for Child Death Review (CDR) and local and state child death review teams. This surveillance program aims to reduce SUID, extend state-level child fatality review of infant deaths, and provide data to track key “Healthy People 2020” objectives.", `reportFrequency`:"", `shortName`:"SUIDCR", `specialPopulations`:"", `startDate`:"", `startDateGeneration`:"2010", `state`:"", `surveillanceDomain`:"", `surveillanceType`:"", `webResource`:"NULL"})

The national trichinellosis surveillance system is a passive system that relies on existing resources at the local, state, and federal levels. Cases are diagnosed based on clinical history with laboratory confirmation of Trichinella infection. Cases are reported weekly to CDC through the National Electronic Telecommunications System for Surveillance (NETSS). Detailed data regarding signs and symptoms, diagnostic tests, and food consumption are gathered by using a supplementary standardized surveillance form and are reported to CDC by fax or mail. This information is compared with NETSS data several times a year by CDC staff. Discrepancies are reviewed with the state health departments. The purpose of the surveillance system is to determine the incidence of trichinellosis, to maintain awareness of the disease, to monitor epidemiologic changes, to identify outbreaks, to guide prevention efforts, and to measure the effectiveness of those efforts.", `reportFrequency`:"", `shortName`:"", `specialPopulations`:"", `startDate`:"", `startDateGeneration`:"1997", `state`:"", `surveillanceDomain`:"", `surveillanceType`:"", `webResource`:"http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/ss5809a1.htm"})

create (_2981:`SurveillanceSystem` {`Notes`:"", `ageFormat`:"", `applicationPlatform`:"", `applicationSolutionType`:"", `avrCapability`:"", `city`:"", `conditionsUnderSurveillance`:"", `contactEmail`:"", `contactName`:"", `contactPhone`:"", `dataPayloadFormat`:"", `dataPayloadTransmissionType`:"", `dataProvidersElectronic`:"", `dataProvidersManual`:"", `dataRecipientsElectronic`:"", `dataRecipientsManual`:"", `databaseTechnology`:"", `evaluationDate`:"", `evaluationDetails`:"", `fullName`:"", `fundingLevels`:"", `fundingSource`:"", `geographicCoverageArea`:"", `id`:"SS152", `informationValidated`:"No", `informationValidatedBy`:"", `informationValidatedOn`:"", `lastUpdated`:"", `lastUpdatedBy`:"", `name`:"Survey of Coal Mine Safety Interventions", `nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:"", `operatingSystemPlatform`:"", `operationalStatus`:"Planned for Future Development", `overallCapability`:"", `patientTrackingCapability`:"", `purpose`:"Although the NIOSH Office of Mine Safety and Health Research widely disseminates and publicizes research results, recommendations, techniques and products, the agency has limited knowledge about the extent to which their innovations in mine safety and health have been implemented by individual mine operators. This is particularly true of methods and practices that are not mandated by formal regulations. The overarching goal of Survey of Coal Mine Safety Interventions is to gather data from working coal mines on the adoption and implementation of OMSHR practices to mitigate safety and occupational hazards (e.g., explosions, falls of ground). The information from this survey will be used by OMSHR to evaluate the implementation of safety and health interventions (including best practices and barriers to implementation) in areas such as respirable coal dust control, explosion prevention, roof support, and emergency response planning and training. Survey results will provide OMSHR with knowledge about which recommended practices, tools and methods have been most widely embraced by the mining industry, which have not been adopted, and why. The survey results will provide needed insight from the perspective of mine operators on the practical barriers that may prevent wider adoption of OMSHR recommendations and practices designed to safeguard mine workers.", `reportFrequency`:"", `shortName`:"", `specialPopulations`:"", `startDate`:"", `startDateGeneration`:"NULL", `state`:"", `surveillanceDomain`:"", `surveillanceType`:"", `webResource`:"NULL"})

The objectives of TBGIMS are to improve access to and dissemination of genotyping information nationwide; to serve as a standard database federal, state and local programs can use to access genotype results of Mycobacterium tuberculosis complex isolates; receive and update genotyping information; monitor genotype clusters and to provide a way to alert users about potential TB outbreaks in their jurisdictions. create (_2985:`SurveillanceSystem` {`CR_DATE_CREATED`:1428427983488, `CR_DATE_EDITED`:"", `CR_DATE_EXECUTED`:1428442489712, `CR_NODE_TYPE`:"SurveillanceSystem", `CR_PREVIOUS`:"{\"name\":\"Universal Data Collection\",\"id\":\"SS156\",\"purpose\":\"People with hemophilia, von Willebrand disease, and other congenital bleeding disorders are at risk for recurrent bleeding episodes, which can predispose to long-term morbidity and increased mortality.   In particular, people with hemophilia are susceptible to the development of chronic, and often debilitating joint disease from repeated bleeding into major joints such as the knee and ankle.  The treatment of a bleeding episode involves the replacement of the missing protein through the intravenous administration of factor concentrate which is derived from, or contains components of human blood plasma.  As a result, people with hemophilia using these treatment products are at risk for infection with viral, blood-borne diseases such as hepatitis and human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) that can be transmitted in the blood products.  Nearly 70% of all persons with hemophilia in the U.S. receive at least some of their medical care from federally-sponsored, specialized hemophilia treatment centers (HTCs) located throughout the country.  These centers currently provide care to over 27,000 children and adults with these disorders.  The purpose of the Universal Data Collection (UDC) project was to collect a uniform set of clinical data on people with hemophilia and other congenital bleeding disorders receiving care at 130+ U.S. HTCs.  These data are used to characterize the population, monitor blood and blood product safety, and identify complications.   All persons with hemophilia A or B and related congenital bleeding disorders who received care at an HTC were eligible for inclusion in the data collection effort.  Routine clinical data were collected using a combination of medical record abstraction or direct patient interview by HTC staff as a part of the routine clinical assessment. Information was recorded on standardized data collection forms or electronic data systems.  There were two parts to the data collection: patient registration and current clinical information recording.  The Registration Form was completed one time only for each patient and served to introduce the patient into the data system.  Data collected on this form includes baseline demographic and clinical information that did not change over time.  The current clinical information was collected by using the Annual Visit Form for participants 2 years old and older, and by using the Baby Visit Form for children under two years old.  The Annual Visit Form was completed for each patient ≥ 2 years old by treatment center staff at the first visit and once per year thereafter and collected detailed information on clinical outcomes concerning joint disease and viral and other complications.  The Baby Visit Form was completed by treatment center staff at the first visit and at 6 month intervals until age 2 years.  The Baby Visit Form collected information on current treatment, bleed history, and clinical outcomes.  In addition, patients were asked to complete standardized and validated age-appropriate quality of life instruments as part of the study.  Testing of serum specimens collected annually from persons receiving care in the HTCs for the presence of blood borne pathogens was offered by CDC to assist HTCs in monitoring related infections.  After testing, the remainder of each serum specimen was stored by the CDC to establish a serum bank for possible future use in evaluating the safety of blood products used by these persons. UDC data was collected annually from 1998 through September 2011. Enrollment of subjects into this project ended at the end of September 2011, but data analysis and potential testing of blood specimens is expected to continue into the foreseeable future.  Bleeding disorders surveillance has transitioned to a new project entitled “Community Counts– CDC Public Health Surveillance for Bleeding Disorders” (Community Counts).  In order to monitor complications and trends over a longer period of time, information from UDC will be linked to Community Counts where appropriate if the participant provides authorization. Each week, approximately 2,000 outpatient care sites around the country report data to CDC on the total number of patients seen and the number of those patients with influenza-like illness (ILI) by age group. For this system, ILI is defined as fever (temperature of 100°F [37.8°C] or greater) and a cough and/or a sore throat in the absence of a KNOWN cause other than influenza. Sites with electronic records use an equivalent definition as determined by the state public health authorities. The percentage of patient visits to healthcare providers for ILI reported each week is weighted on the basis of state population. This percentage is compared each week with the annually calculated national baseline. The baseline is the mean percentage of patient visits for ILI during non-influenza weeks for the previous three seasons plus two standard deviations. Due to wide variability in regional level data, it is not appropriate to apply the national baseline to regional data, therefore, region specific baselines are calculated.", `reportFrequency`:"", `shortName`:"ILINet", `specialPopulations`:"", `startDate`:"", `startDateGeneration`:"1982", `state`:"", `surveillanceDomain`:"", `surveillanceType`:"", `webResource`:"http://www.cdc.gov/flu"})

create (_3033:`Tool` {`Notes`:"", `ageFormat`:"", `applicationPlatform`:"", `applicationSolutionType`:"", `avrCapability`:"", `city`:"", `conditionsUnderSurveillance`:"", `contactEmail`:"", `contactName`:"", `contactPhone`:"", `dataPayloadFormat`:"", `dataPayloadTransmissionType`:"", `databaseTechnology`:"", `evaluationDate`:"", `evaluationDetails`:"", `fullName`:"Exposure Investigation", `fundingLevels`:"", `fundingSource`:"", `geographicCoverageArea`:"", `id`:"TL16", `informationValidated`:"No", `informationValidatedBy`:"", `informationValidatedOn`:"", `lastUpdated`:"", `lastUpdatedBy`:"", `name`:"Exposure Investigation", `nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:"", `operatingSystemPlatform`:"", `operationalStatus`:"Retired", `overallCapability`:"", `patientTrackingCapability`:"", `purpose`:"An exposure investigation is one approach ATSDR uses to develop better characterization of past, current, and possible future human exposures to hazardous substances in the environment and to evaluate existing and possible health effects related to those exposures more thoroughly. There are three main ways information is gathered during an exposure investigation: Bio-medical testing (for example, urine or blood samples) is an important piece of information gathered and evaluated during an ATSDR exposure investigation. Bio-medical samples can show current (and sometimes past) exposure to a contaminant. Environmental testing (for contamination of soil, water, or air) is also an important piece of information gathered and evaluated during an exposure investigation. ATSDR investigators focus environmental testing on where people live, spend time and play, or might come in contact with contaminants under investigation. Our branch also has expertise in exposure dose reconstruction. Exposure-dose reconstruction analyses use environmental sampling information and computer models to estimate the contaminant levels that people may have been exposed to in the past or may be exposed to in the future. We can use these models to draw various conclusions. For example, how long and at what levels a drinking water well has been contaminated. We can then use the information to evaluate how a person's health might be affected.", `reportFrequency`:"", `shortName`:"", `specialPopulations`:"", `startDate`:"", `startDateGeneration`:"NULL", `state`:"", `surveillanceDomain`:"", `surveillanceType`:"", `webResource`:"NULL"})

Its purpose is to ensure the quality and availability of LRN data and decrease the time needed to detect and respond to public health threats. The LRN is a coordinated network of public health and other laboratories for which CDC provides standard assays and protocols for testing biological and chemical terrorism agents. LRN Results Messenger (LRN RM) is a software solution created to provide LRN labs with the immediate ability to manage and share standard laboratory data. LRN RM is currently installed over 160 LRN laboratories, including 100% of the LRN’s public health labs. LRN RM provides basic laboratory data management, including the ability to enter and share sample and results data. The application enables labs to submit and respond to electronic test requests from other LRN labs, which supports the mutual assistance functionality of the LRN. The application embodies PHIN requirements and utilizes CDC’s Secure Data Network and PHIN Messaging System infrastructure. LRN Results Viewer is deployed within the CDC and provides a database to store LRN results and the ability to query and view those results. The Laboratory Information Management System Integration (LIMSi) activity is a parallel effort to LRN RM. It represents the next generation of the incremental approach to data exchange for the LRN. Its purpose is to enable laboratories to fulfill data exchange needs for the LRN using their own systems by implementing data standards and infrastructure to support Health Level 7 (HL7) messaging. LIMSi  has facilitated collaborative efforts between CDC and public health laboratory subject matter experts to refine system requirements needed to configure laboratory information management systems (LIMS) to manage LRN testing. The LIMSi project is also collaborating closely with related CDC efforts, such as the Public Health Laboratory Interoperability Project since the two efforts share many common initiatives. The online abstracting capability of Web Plus is suitable for reporting from physicians’ offices and other low-volume reporting sources, while the file upload feature can be used for electronic submission of data from all other reporting sources (often along with the offline abstraction capability of Abstract Plus).
