create (_3051:`Tool` {`Notes`:"", `ageFormat`:"", `applicationPlatform`:"", `applicationSolutionType`:"", `avrCapability`:"", `city`:"", `conditionsUnderSurveillance`:"", `contactEmail`:"", `contactName`:"", `contactPhone`:"", `dataPayloadFormat`:"", `dataPayloadTransmissionType`:"", `databaseTechnology`:"", `evaluationDate`:"", `evaluationDetails`:"", `fullName`:"NIOSH Worker Health Chart Book", `fundingLevels`:"", `fundingSource`:"", `geographicCoverageArea`:"", `id`:"TL35", `informationValidated`:"No", `informationValidatedBy`:"", `informationValidatedOn`:"", `lastUpdated`:"", `lastUpdatedBy`:"", `name`:"NIOSH Worker Health Chart Book", `nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:"", `operatingSystemPlatform`:"", `operationalStatus`:"Fully Operational and Implemented", `overallCapability`:"", `patientTrackingCapability`:"", `purpose`:"The NIOSH Surveillance Program has developed a Worker Health eChartbook web site as a descriptive epidemiologic reference on occupational morbidity and mortality in the United States. It serves as a resource for agencies, organizations, employers, researchers, workers, and others who need to know about occupational injuries and illnesses. The 1st Worker Health Chartbook was prepared and published in 2000. The principal means of disseminating its content was through a type-set print document. Also, a web version (see http://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docs/2000-127/) was developed, permitting the downloading of images and tables in Microsoft Excel format. The development of the 2nd Worker Health Chartbook (also see http://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docs/2004-146/pdfs/2004-146.pdf) began shortly after the completion of the calendar year 2000 Worker Health Chartbook publication. From the beginning, the 2ndHealth version of the Worker Health Chartbook was intended to permit access and dissemination of contents to the maximum extent possible. In addition to a print version, NIOSH developed a website based on the content of the 2nd Chartbook. Our intent was to increase both access and availability of the content to the user community. The web version permits visitors to copy text, download the actual charts (*.gif format) and tables, link to external sources based on the extensively documented tables and references, and appendices. The Worker Health eChartbook (hereafter eChartbook) is a continuation of these previous efforts. Begun in late 2005, a small cadre of staff has been developing the new Worker Health eChartbook primarily as a web-based occupational safety and health statistics resources. Many of the features associated with the 2nd Worker Health Chartbook (see http://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docs/2004-146/) are found here, with the exception of a print document. The current contents include more than 18,000 figures and tables describing the magnitude, distribution, and trends of the Nation's occupational injuries, illnesses, and fatalities. In 2011 we plan to expand the resource to include more extensive listing of morbidity and mortality data (chapter 4), state-specific content, as well as general population health status and risk. Also, work is proceeding to develop and include content economics and quality of work life. The eChartbook will continue to grow and develop to reflect the growing data and information needs of the NIOSH Program Portfolio (see http://www.cdc.gov/niosh/programs/). CPONDER contains 2007 and 2008 data for PRAMS state/year combinations that achieve at least a 65% response rate. As additional years of data are weighted, they will be added to the system. PRAMS collects state-specific, population-based data on maternal attitudes and experiences before, during, and shortly after pregnancy. PRAMS was initiated in 1987 because infant mortality rates were no longer declining as rapidly as they had in prior years. In addition, the incidence of low birth weight infants had changed little in the previous 20 years. Research has indicated that maternal behaviors during pregnancy may influence infant birth weight and mortality rates. The goal of the PRAMS project is to improve the health of mothers and infants by reducing adverse outcomes such as low birth weight, infant mortality and morbidity, and maternal morbidity. PRAMS provides state-specific data for planning and assessing health programs and for describing maternal experiences that may contribute to maternal and infant health. PONDER, a web-based query system located on the Inside PRAMS website that is available to CDC and state project staff. PONDER includes weighted data from the PRAMS questionnaire and provides real-time prevalence estimates and robust standard errors through a user friendly, web-enabled, point and click interface. PONDER enables users to perform cross tabulations and generate basic descriptive statistics (e.g., means, weighted and raw counts). Cigarette smoking and exposure to tobacco smoke resulted in at least 443,000 premature deaths, approximately 5.1 million years of potential life lost (YPLL), and $96.8 billion in productivity losses annually in the United States (CDC, 2008). Since 1987, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) has used the Smoking-Attributable Mortality, Morbidity, and Economic Costs (SAMMEC) application to estimate the disease impact of smoking for the nation, states, and large populations. The SAMMEC application has been used to estimate smoking-attributable mortality (SAM), YPLL, direct medical expenditures, and productivity losses. However, the primary focus of SAMMEC has been to measure the deaths and years of life lost due to smoking. create (_3066:`Tool` {`Notes`:"", `ageFormat`:"", `applicationPlatform`:"", `applicationSolutionType`:"", `avrCapability`:"", `city`:"", `conditionsUnderSurveillance`:"", `contactEmail`:"", `contactName`:"", `contactPhone`:"", `dataPayloadFormat`:"", `dataPayloadTransmissionType`:"", `databaseTechnology`:"", `evaluationDate`:"", `evaluationDetails`:"", `fullName`:"State Indicator Report on Fruits and Vegetables, 2009", `fundingLevels`:"", `fundingSource`:"", `geographicCoverageArea`:"", `id`:"TL50", `informationValidated`:"No", `informationValidatedBy`:"", `informationValidatedOn`:"", `lastUpdated`:"", `lastUpdatedBy`:"", `name`:"State Indicator Report on Fruits and Vegetables, 2009", `nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:"", `operatingSystemPlatform`:"", `operationalStatus`:"Fully Operational and Implemented", `overallCapability`:"", `patientTrackingCapability`:"", `purpose`:"The State Indicator Report on Fruits and Vegetables provides information on fruit and vegetable (F and V) consumption and policy and environmental support within each state. Fruits and vegetables are important for optimal child growth, weight management, and chronic disease prevention. Supporting increased F and V access, availability, and reduced price are key strategies towards the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's (CDC) objective of improved F and V consumption and thus improved nutrition among all Americans. National and state-specific information is reported in the State Indicator Report for behavioral indicators and policy and environmental indicators. The behavioral indicators are derived from objectives for F and V consumption outlined in Healthy People 2010, a framework for the nation's health priorities, and data is from CDC's health surveillance systems. The policy and environmental indicators are from multiple data sources and measure several aspects of a state's ability to support the consumption of F and V. Each indicator can be measured in most states. Individual states, however, may have data collected through state-wide surveys and/or have policies enacted outside the monitoring period that can augment the information in this State Indicator Report and thus can be used to further inform decision makers. Throughout states and communities, many groups play a role in supporting policy and environmental change to ensure that individuals and families can easily purchase and consume F and V. When state officials, health professionals, employers, retail owners, farmers, school staff, and community members work together their efforts can increase the number of Americans who live healthier lives by increasing the availability of affordable healthier food choices such as F and V. Data in the State Indicator Report can be used by states to track progress on a variety of indicators in order to portray how states support the consumption of F and V, celebrate state successes, and identify opportunities for improvement of F and V support through environmental, policy and/or systems approaches.", `reportFrequency`:"", `shortName`:"SIRFV", `specialPopulations`:"", `startDate`:"", `startDateGeneration`:"NULL", `state`:"", `surveillanceDomain`:"", `surveillanceType`:"", `webResource`:"http://www.cdc.gov/obesity/resources/reports.html"})

This system markedly increases the speed and efficiency by which users can obtain important injury data for research, prevention program needs, and decision-making purposes. WISQARS eliminates the need for time-consuming computer programming to obtain requested information. Both internal and external users can obtain the data they need via the internet in the format that meets their needs. WISQARS provides current data (e.g., numbers, rates, age-adjusted rates) on fatal and nonfatal injuries. Fatal data are from death certificate data from NVSS of NCHS. The first year of available NVSS death data is 1981. Nonfatal data are from the National Electronic Injury Surveillance System-All Injury Program. The first year of available nonfatal data is 2000. WISQARS also provides data on violent deaths from the National Violence Death Reporting System. The first year of available NVDRS violent death data is 2003. WISQARS also has a new module that provides color choropleth county-level maps of death rates by mechanism and intent of injury and a module that provides lifetime cost of injury data for injury deaths, hospitalizations, and emergency department visits. A WISQARS mobile application is being developed for tablets and smart phones.  This app will provides ready access to injury-related deaths and death rates by selected mechanism and intent in maps, charts and graphs on mobile devices. For this study, which was conducted in Atlanta during 1984-1990, investigators devised methods for determining the prevalence of intellectual disability, cerebral palsy, legal blindness, hearing loss, and epilepsy among children 10 years of age. Children who had these conditions were identified by searching record systems of sources that were likely to contain information relating to the evaluation or treatment of children with developmental disabilities (e.g., schools, hospitals, and state programs for persons who have developmental disabilities). The majority of the children were identified through special education departments within the Atlanta area public school systems. The success of this study prompted CDC to establish the Metropolitan Atlanta Developmental Disabilities Surveillance Program (MADDSP) in 1991, an ongoing system for monitoring the occurrence of selected developmental disabilities. MADDSP is located at CDC in the Developmental Disabilities Branch within the National Center on Birth Defects and Developmental Disabilities. The two principal objectives of MADDSP are to a) provide regular and systematic monitoring of the prevalence of selected developmental disabilities according to various demographic characteristics of children and their mothers and b) provide a framework for initiating special studies of children who have the selected developmental disabilities by establishing a population-based case series of such children. Currently, MADDSP monitors intellectual disability, cerebral palsy, hearing loss, vision impairment and autism spectrum FTP is built on a client-server architecture and uses separate control and data connections between the client and the server.[1] FTP users may authenticate themselves using a clear-text sign-in protocol, normally in the form of a username and password, but can connect anonymously if the server is configured to allow it. For secure transmission that protects the username and password, and encrypts the content, FTP is often secured with SSL/TLS (FTPS). SSH File Transfer Protocol (SFTP) is sometimes also used instead, but is technologically different. CDC has the regulatory responsibility for preventing the introduction, transmission, and spread of communicable diseases into the United States as well as for developing the guidelines, known as technical instructions, for the overseas medical examinations. Other conditions that are not infectious might preclude an immigrant or refugee from entering the United States and also are reported as part of the medical examination. After arrival in the United States, all refugees are recommended to obtain a medical assessment by a health-care provider or a health department within 30 days. In addition, immigrants with certain medical conditions such as noninfectious tuberculosis at the time of the original medical examination are recommended to be evaluated after arrival to ensure that appropriate prevention or treatment measures are instituted. The freely available Web site 'healthmap.org' and mobile app 'Outbreaks Near Me' deliver real-time intelligence on a broad range of emerging infectious diseases for a diverse audience including libraries, local health departments, governments, and international travelers. HealthMap brings together disparate data sources, including online news aggregators, eyewitness reports, expert-curated discussions and validated official reports, to achieve a unified and comprehensive view of the current global state of infectious diseases and their effect on human and animal health. The Organization brings together birth defect surveillance and research programs from around the world with the aim of investigating and preventing birth defects and lessening the impact of their consequences. The Organization was first established in 1974, at a meeting in Helsinki, Finland, where representatives of malformation registries in ten countries were present. It was named the International Clearinghouse for Birth Defects Monitoring Systems (ICBDMS) and member programs were actively engaged in the systematic collection and analysis of data for the comprehensive monitoring of congenital malformations. In 2003/4, a strategic planning group was set up with the aim of suggesting new strategic goals for the Organization. These suggestions were approved at the Clearinghouse Annual Meeting in Japan, 2004 and the Organization under the current name of International Clearinghouse for Birth Defects Surveillance and Research (ICBDSR), was officially established. It now has 44 member programs worldwide. The mission of the International Clearinghouse of Birth Defects Surveillance and Research is to conduct worldwide surveillance and research into the occurrence and possible causes of Birth Defects with the aim of preventing them and decreasing their consequences. The strategic priority of the Clearinghouse is to conduct worldwide surveillance and to exchange data about birth defects. The scope of the Clearinghouse includes fetal and childhood conditions of prenatal cause. Participating surveillance programs will carry out systematic data collection and use the data for public health action. Public health action includes comparing prevalence rates, advocacy, policy development, conducting epidemiological studies of causes and consequences of birth defects, assessing preventive and therapeutic interventions, and interacting with the public, research institutions and relevant government It collects data on the occurrence of cancer; the type, extent, and location of the cancer; and the type of initial treatment. NPCR supports central cancer registries in 45 states, the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, and the U.S. Pacific Island Jurisdictions. These data represent 96% of the U.S. population. In each U.S. state, DC, and territory, local and regional cancer data are reported to central cancer registries about all new diagnoses of cancer from patient records at such medical facilities as hospitals, physicians'offices, therapeutic radiation facilities, freestanding surgical centers, and pathology laboratories. These data are submitted annually in November to CDC’s NPCR. Data collected by local cancer registries enable public health professionals to understand and address the cancer burden more effectively. Since its inception in 2002, the registry has evolved into the largest post disaster follow-up in US history and is recognized as the primary source for epidemiological findings regarding the effects of 9-11 related exposures for both physical and mental health disease. Peer reviewed objective and scientifically valid data from the registry on the long term health burden of 9-11 has resulted in continued medical monitoring and treatment of 9-11 rescue/recovery workers, lower Manhattan residents, and children who were enrolled in schools in the vicinity of WTC. The registry has also been used by external researchers who have completed studies in such areas as building evacuation safety and procedures and biological basis for Post traumatic stress disorder. The registry will be important for assessing potential long term effects on health, especially cancer, through its capability of matching with mortality and state cancer registry data. This activity collects information to determine if conditions under surveillance were occupationally and environmentally acquired.", `registryType`:"", `reportFrequency`:"", `shortName`:"WTCHR", `specialPopulations`:"", `startDate`:"", `startDateGeneration`:"2003", `state`:"", `surveillanceDomain`:"", `surveillanceType`:"", `webResource`:"http://www.nyc.gov/html/doh/wtc/html/registry/about.shtml"})

create (_3167:`Collaborative` {`Notes`:"", `ageFormat`:"", `collaborativeParticipants`:"", `conditionsUnderSurveillance`:"", `contactEmail`:"", `contactName`:"", `contactPhone`:"", `dataPayloadFormat`:"", `dataPayloadTransmissionType`:"", `dataProvidersElectronic`:"", `dataProvidersManual`:"", `dataRecipientsElectronic`:"", `dataRecipientsManual`:"", `fullName`:"Biosurveillance Coordination Activity", `geographicCoverageArea`:"", `id`:"CO2", `informationValidated`:"No", `informationValidatedBy`:"", `informationValidatedOn`:"", `lastUpdated`:"", `lastUpdatedBy`:"", `name`:"Biosurveillance Coordination Activity", `operationStartDate`:"NULL", `operationalStatus`:"Fully Operational and Implemented", `patientTrackingCapability`:"", `purpose`:"In 2007, Homeland Security Presidential Directive 21 (HSPD-21) was issued in recognition of the emergence of significant health-related threats to the nation. HSPD-21 called for the development of a nationwide approach to biosurveillance in order to enhance the United States’ ability to detect and respond to those threats. HSPD-21 defines biosurveillance as— …the process of active data-gathering with appropriate analysis and interpretation of biosphere data that might relate to disease activity and threats to human or animal health—whether infectious, toxic, metabolic, or otherwise, and regardless or intentional or natural origin—in order to achieve early warning of health threats, early detection of health events, and overall situational awareness of disease activity. The Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) was charged with the responsibility of enhancing biosurveillance for human health and delegated this responsibility to CDC. In 2008, CDC established the Biosurveillance Coordination unit (BC) to oversee the necessary activities to address these mandates. With input from federal, state, local, tribal, and private stakeholders, the BC unit coordinated the release of the first draft version of the National Biosurveillance Strategy for Human Health (NBSHH) in December 2008. The NBSHH established priorities for the nation’s next-generation biosurveillance capability to provide timely, comprehensive, and accessible information to strengthen public health practice, provide value to clinicians, and build upon current systems and resources. Version 2 of the National Biosurveillance Strategy for Human Health (NBSHH) was extensively revised and expanded to include additional information. It was released in February 2010.", `shortName`:"", `startDateGeneration`:"", `surveillanceDomain`:"", `webResource`:""})

FELTPs help support CDC's global health diplomacy by fostering close partnerships with MOHs, U.S. diplomatic facilities abroad, and international agencies. Staff provide technical assistance and support to help countries develop, set up, and implement dynamic public health strategies to improve and strengthen their public health workforce, systems, and infrastructure. FELTPs promote epidemiology and public health laboratory collaboration by providing joint epidemiology laboratory leadership and management training, including public health laboratorians in field investigations; using laboratory data for disease surveillance; and improving biosafety and quality assurance control in specimen collection and transport, laboratory analysis, reporting, and interpretation.", `shortName`:"", `startDateGeneration`:"", `surveillanceDomain`:"", `webResource`:""})

The current Rubella Virus Laboratory was formed in 1998 in the measles section. After a major reorganization the rubella laboratory team was officially moved to the Measles, Mumps, Rubella (MMR) and Herpesvirus Laboratory Branch (MMRHLB), Division of Viral Diseases, National Center for Immunization and Respiratory Diseases. The Rubella Laboratory provides serologic and molecular testing for rubella as a national reference laboratory and provides technical assistance to state public health laboratories for the collection and shipment of clinical samples for rubella RT-PCR and sequencing. The Rubella Laboratory team works with the Epidemiology Branch to coordinate laboratory support for local and state public health laboratories during outbreaks and investigations of suspected spread cases following an importation of rubella. Our program has been involved in providing guidance to different countries on conducting pediatric HIV surveillance activities to contribute to their understanding of the magnitude of the epidemic among children, thereby guiding policy and program decision-making. Thus far, we have been involved in developing and writing publications and presentations advocating for pediatric HIV surveillance, describing pediatric HIV surveillance approaches, and providing strategies for designing systems to track pediatric HIV. create (_3188:`Collaborative` {`Notes`:"", `ageFormat`:"", `collaborativeParticipants`:"", `conditionsUnderSurveillance`:"", `contactEmail`:"", `contactName`:"", `contactPhone`:"", `dataPayloadFormat`:"", `dataPayloadTransmissionType`:"", `dataProvidersElectronic`:"", `dataProvidersManual`:"", `dataRecipientsElectronic`:"", `dataRecipientsManual`:"", `fullName`:"Rapid Onset of Gastroenteritis with Unexplained Etiology", `geographicCoverageArea`:"", `id`:"CO24", `informationValidated`:"No", `informationValidatedBy`:"", `informationValidatedOn`:"", `lastUpdated`:"", `lastUpdatedBy`:"", `name`:"Rapid Onset of Gastroenteritis with Unexplained Etiology", `operationStartDate`:"NULL", `operationalStatus`:"Retired", `patientTrackingCapability`:"", `purpose`:"The purpose of Rapid Onset of Gastroenteritis with Unexplained Etiology (ROGUE) working group was to 1) Reduce the number of foodborne illnesses with unknown etiology and 2) Provide epidemiologic and laboratory assistance when possible. The Rapid Onset of Gastroenteritis with Unexplained Etiology (ROGUE) working group investigates foodborne diseases that may have a chemical etiology. Since the most common foodborne illnesses are due to biological organisms, these are much more commonly considered early in an outbreak. Recognition of chemical etiologies is often not made until later, and this hinders ultimate identification of responsible agents because of the timeliness with which samples must be collected. Better clues are needed to help clinicians and public health officials determine if a foodborne outbreak may have a chemical etiology. People that become ill from chemical contaminants in food may comment that the food had an unusual taste, smell or appearance. These organoleptic qualities can be important clues in identifying the types of agents that may have contaminated the food and caused illness, as well as helpful in identifying that a chemical induced foodborne illness may be occurring. Unfortunately, in the investigation of foodborne illness complaints, this type of information is seldom collected in a uniform manner.", `shortName`:"ROGUE", `startDateGeneration`:"", `surveillanceDomain`:"", `webResource`:""})

create (_3192:`Collaborative` {`Notes`:"", `ageFormat`:"", `collaborativeParticipants`:"", `conditionsUnderSurveillance`:"", `contactEmail`:"", `contactName`:"", `contactPhone`:"", `dataPayloadFormat`:"", `dataPayloadTransmissionType`:"", `dataProvidersElectronic`:"", `dataProvidersManual`:"", `dataRecipientsElectronic`:"", `dataRecipientsManual`:"", `fullName`:"WHO Collaborating Center for Rotavirus and the Agents of Viral Gastroenteritis", `geographicCoverageArea`:"", `id`:"CO28", `informationValidated`:"No", `informationValidatedBy`:"", `informationValidatedOn`:"", `lastUpdated`:"", `lastUpdatedBy`:"", `name`:"WHO Collaborating Center for Rotavirus and the Agents of Viral Gastroenteritis", `operationStartDate`:"NULL", `operationalStatus`:"Fully Operational and Implemented", `patientTrackingCapability`:"", `purpose`:"CDC’s - Rotavirus Program serves as a World Health Organization (WHO) Collaborating Center for rotavirus and other viral agents of gastroenteritis. WHO designated the Rotavirus Program a Collaborating Center beginning in 1998 and redesignation occurs every five years. The primary role of the CDC Rotavirus Collaborating Center is to support the WHO Global Rotavirus Surveillance Network that collects data on rotavirus disease burden and strain prevalence as part of efforts to introduce rotavirus vaccines globally. Globally, rotavirus is the cause of about  450,000 diarrheal deaths every year,  almost all of which occur in  developing countries. In addition, many more children will get dehydrated and require medical intervention and hospitalization. Several vaccines against rotavirus have been, or are being, developed to reduce this burden. Since 2006, two live attenuated vaccines against rotavirus have been licensed in more than 100 countries around the world and are now recommended by WHO for global use. One component of efforts to introduce rotavirus vaccines globally is the derivation of global, regional and local disease burden and strain prevalence estimates to help make the case for vaccination and to support countries decisions about rotavirus vaccine introduction.. The CDC and WHO have developed a generic protocol for standardized surveillance of rotavirus disease burden and strain prevalence, and with support from the Global Alliance for Vaccines and Immunization (GAVI) and in collaboration with CDC and country partners, WHO has recently developed a Global Rotavirus Surveillance Network made up of regional networks (about 60 countries) in the six WHO regions (Americas, Africa, European, Eastern Mediterranean, Southeast Asia and Western Pacific Regions) to collect current data.  The role of the CDC Rotavirus Program and its Collaborating Center is to provide the WHO with technical expertise and laboratory and epidemiologic support to aid in network activities. Another Rotavirus Collaborating Center from Melbourne, Australia and Rotavirus Reference Laboratories from the six WHO regions provide region-specific laboratory support. Terms of reference of the center: 1. To conduct evaluations of rotavirus vaccines in collaboration with the Department of Vaccines and Biologicals (V&B, WHO) and developing country investigators. 2. To conduct rotavirus disease and strain surveillance with support from the Childhood Vaccine Program, Program of Appropriate Technology in Health (PATH) of the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation, and V&B, WHO 3. To serve as a vaccine evaluation training center for scientists for developing and developed countries. 4. The ICD is designed as a health care classification system, providing a system of diagnostic codes for classifying diseases, including nuanced classifications of a wide variety of signs, symptoms, abnormal findings, complaints, social circumstances, and external causes of injury or disease. This system is designed to map health conditions to corresponding generic categories together with specific variations, assigning for these a designated code, up to six characters long. Thus, major categories are designed to include a set of similar diseases. create (_3263:`DataStandard` {`description`:"Diagnosis-related group (DRG) is a system to classify hospital cases into one of originally 467 groups,with the 467th group being \"Ungroupable\". This system of classification was developed as a collaborative project by Robert B Fetter, PhD, of the Yale School of Management, and John D. Thompson, MPH, of the Yale School of Public Health.The system is also referred to as \"the DRGs\", and its intent was to identify the \"products\" that a hospital provides. One example of a \"product\" is an appendectomy. The system was developed in anticipation of convincing Congress to use it for reimbursement, to replace \"cost based\" reimbursement that had been used up to that point. DRGs are assigned by a \"grouper\" program based on ICD (International Classification of Diseases) diagnoses, procedures, age, sex, discharge status, and the presence of complications or comorbidities. DRGs have been used in the US since 1982 to determine how much Medicare pays the hospital for each \"product\", since patients within each category are clinically similar and are expected to use the same level of hospital resources.DRGs may be further grouped into Major Diagnostic Categories (MDCs). DRGs are also standard practice for establishing reimbursements for other Medicare related reimbursements such as to home healthcare providers.", `id`:"DSTD14", `informationValidated`:"Yes", `informationValidatedBy`:"Tom Savel", `informationValidatedOn`:"9/30/2014", `lastUpdated`:"", `lastUpdatedBy`:"Tom Savel", `licenseType`:"", `name`:"Diagnosis-Related Group", `notes`:"", `referenceURL`:"", `terminologyFullName`:"", `terminologyShortName`:"", `terminologyVersionNumber`:"", `terminoloyID`:""})

The coding system utilized by the DSM-IV is designed to correspond with codes from the International Classification of Diseases, commonly referred to as the ICD. An objective of the CLIA is to ensure the accuracy, reliability and timeliness of test results regardless of where the test was performed. create (_3273:`DataStandard` {`description`:"The Standard Occupational Classification (SOC) System is a United States government system of classifying occupations. It is used by U.S. federal government agencies collecting occupational data, enabling comparison of occupations across data sets. It is designed to cover all occupations in which work is performed for pay or profit, reflecting the current occupational structure in the United States. The 2010 SOC includes 840 occupational types.   Users of occupational data include government program managers, industrial and labor relations practitioners, students considering career training, job seekers, vocational training schools, and employers wishing to set salary scales or locate a new plant.   The SOC codes have a hierarchical format, so for example the code \"15-0000\" refers to occupations in the \"Computer and Mathematical Occupations\" category, and \"15-1130\" is a subset for \"Software Developers and Programmers.\"    The SOC does not categorize industries or employers. There are orthogonal category systems for industries used with SOC data, most commonly NAICS. create (_3394:`Program` {`CR_DATE_CREATED`:1430499621648, `CR_DATE_EDITED`:"", `CR_DATE_EXECUTED`:1431460926149, `CR_NODE_TYPE`:"Program", `CR_PREVIOUS`:"{\"name\":\"Occupational Hearing Loss Surveillance\",\"id\":\"P53\",\"purpose\":\"In 2006, the National Academy of Sciences identified the lack of hearing loss surveillance as a key shortcoming of the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) Hearing Loss Prevention Research Program. Surveillance is vital to occupational hearing loss (OHL) prevention. It makes possible the establishment of estimates for the prevalence and incidence of hearing loss within various industries. Surveillance also enables NIOSH to identify high risk groups, guide prevention and research efforts, and evaluate the success or failure of interventions. Without surveillance data, progress in hearing loss prevention efforts cannot be quantified, nor the need for improvement in these efforts. In 2009, the NIOSH OHL Surveillance Project commenced to develop a national surveillance system for OHL. The Project uses a novel approach for data collection by partnering with audiometric service providers and others to collect de-identified worker audiograms and related data. This approach has allowed NIOSH to collect millions of de-identified audiograms from thousands of workplaces across the United States while protecting the identities of workers, companies and providers. The North American Industry Classification System (NAICS) is used to classify the industry associated with each audiogram. Data collection, statistical analyses and dissemination of research results are ongoing. As of 2014, NIOSH has partnered with 18 data providers. Over 10.3 million private sector audiograms of varying quality with related demographic data have been collected and added to a national repository for OHL surveillance data. NIOSH also partnered with the United States Air Force beginning in late 2014 to study hearing loss at it relates to military occupations and noise and chemical exposures on the `operationalStatus`:"Operational", `overallCapability`:"", `patientTrackingCapability`:"", `purpose`:"In 2006, the National Academy of Sciences identified the lack of hearing loss surveillance as a key shortcoming of the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) Hearing Loss Prevention Research Program. Surveillance is vital to occupational hearing loss (OHL) prevention. It makes possible the establishment of estimates for the prevalence and incidence of hearing loss within various industries. Surveillance also enables NIOSH to identify high risk groups, guide prevention and research efforts, and evaluate the success or failure of interventions. Without surveillance data, progress in hearing loss prevention efforts cannot be quantified, nor the need for improvement in these efforts. In 2009, the NIOSH OHL Surveillance Project commenced to develop a national surveillance system for OHL. The Project uses a novel approach for data collection by partnering with audiometric service providers and others to collect de-identified worker audiograms and related data. This approach has allowed NIOSH to collect millions of de-identified audiograms from thousands of workplaces across the United States while protecting the identities of workers, companies and providers. The North American Industry Classification System (NAICS) is used to classify the industry associated with each audiogram. Data collection, statistical analyses and dissemination of research results are ongoing. As of 2014, NIOSH has partnered with 18 data providers. Over 10.3 million private sector audiograms of varying quality with related demographic data have been collected and added to a national repository for OHL surveillance data. NIOSH also partnered with the United States Air Force beginning in late 2014 to study hearing loss at it relates to military occupations and noise and chemical exposures on the job.", `rels`:"[{\"aid\":\"P53\",\"aname\":\"Occupational Hearing Loss Surveillance\",\"bid\":\"O11\",\"bname\":\"National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health\",\"reltype\":\"OVERSEES\",\"startid\":\"O11\",\"endid\":\"P53\",\"startname\":\"National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health\",\"endname\":\"Occupational Hearing Loss Surveillance\",\"reldesc\":\"n/a\",\"relid\":1430499597127}]", `reportFrequency`:"", `shortName`:"OHL Surveillance", `specialPopulations`:"", `startDate`:"2009", `startDateGeneration`:"", `state`:"Ohio", `surveillanceDomain`:"", `surveillanceType`:"", `webResource`:"http://www.cdc.gov/niosh/topics/ohl/"})
